	abstract = {Female choice is the pre- and post-copulatory responses of females to male phenotypes and behaviors. The neuroendocrine and anatomical responses of females to mating within the context of sexual selection is poorly characterized. One possible target of female choice is the copulatory plug, which is an epoxy formed of multiple seminal proteins post-ejaculation in the vagina of many mammals. The protein TGM4 is an essential protein for forming the copulatory plug. TGM4 knockout male mice, although indistinguishable anatomically and behaviorally from wild type males, cannot form a copulatory plug, which makes them an ideal study system for understanding its function. Successful copulation and deposit of the copulatory plug is hypothesized to be required for successful implantation of zygotes in mice, a physiological state called pseudopregnancy. Females hours after receiving an ejaculation and copulatory plug from a male exhibit increased neuronal activity of the transcription factor c-Fos in the ventromedial hypothalamus, a proposed site of sexual arousal in female rodents. Subsequently within days the uterine lining begins to thicken in anticipation of implantation of zygotes. We hypothesize that pseudopregnancy may represent a previously unrecognized form of female choice. To characterize better the role of the copulatory plug in pseudopregnancy, we mated females against TGM4 wild type and knockout males. Pseudopregnancy in the brain was assessed through immunohistochemical assay of c-Fos activity in the ventromedial hypothalamus. Pseudopregnancy in the uterus was assessed via non-surgical injection of ConcavaninA beads, which mimic zygote size, into the uterus 2.5 days after copulation and examination of the uterus on day 4.5 for sites of implantation. Our study can perhaps offer insight into the neuroanatomical and uterine basis for female choice in female mice. Support or Funding InformationFunded by the National Science Foundation (NSF).},
